		<text>
		<body>
		<pb n="1"/>
		
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>Novr. 19. 1845</date></p>
			<p>Revd. &amp; Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Enclosed are $3.00 for this<lb/> year&#39;s Occident from <persName>Mr. B. Lichtenstein</persName>&#44; <placeName>Buffalo</placeName>.<lb/>  I should feel obliged if you would send me the <date>Sep<lb/>tember</date> No. <del>which</del> as I have lost it.</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. Lilienthal</persName> late of <placeName>St. Petersburg</placeName> has ar<lb/>rived.  It is very probable that You may secure his<lb/> aid for your paper.  I have seen him last night<lb/> &amp; he told me that he intended to reduce the obser<lb/>vations he has made concerning our co&#45;religionists<lb/> during his stay in <placeName>Russia</placeName> to writing &amp; communicate<lb/> them to the Zeitung des Juden [&#63;].  I remarked to him<lb/> that it would be very desirable for the English<lb/> Jews generally if his essays on the subject<lb/> would appear simultaneously in the English<lb/> Press &amp; that you would certainly publish his com<lb/>munications with pleasure.  The condition of<lb/> our brethren in <placeName>Russia</placeName>&#44; according to his accounts&#44;<lb/> are wretched beyond our conception.  Hitherto<lb/> they have at least enjoyed the liberty of following<lb/> the religion of our fathers&#44; but this boon will<lb/> in all probability very soon been denied them.<lb/>  To renounce their religion or die&#44; will be the<lb/> only alternative left them.  A sad cala<lb/>mity for 2 millions of our brethren.</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. L.</persName> tenders you&#44; through me&#44; his kind regards</p>

		<pb n="2"/>
		
			<p>&amp; should feel himself greatly honoured if you would<lb/> enter into correspondence with him.  He is a man<lb/> that feels a warm interest in our religion &amp; our<lb/> nation &amp; who according to my opinion&#44; would make<lb/> an able champion.</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)">I remain Dear Sir&#44; with sincere respect</p>
						<p>Yours truly</p>
							<p><persName role="author">James K. Gutheim</persName></p>
			<p>To the <addressee>Revd. I. Leeser</addressee></p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>

			<p>P.S. If you should be acquainted with a <persName>Mr.<lb/> Hirshfeld</persName> of <placeName>Marburg</placeName>&#44; who arrived some time<lb/> ago in your city&#44; please to present him my<lb/> compliments</p>

		<pb n="3"/>
		
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>118 South 4<hi rend="">th</hi> Str.</placeName></p>
		  <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName><hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi></placeName></p>
